I'm back. After almost a year off the grid, it's time. A bunch of stuff felt like it was and has been going 'wrong' in succession. 
Me nine months ago: "Balls. Bad luck is balls and I've had a lot of bad luck. Now I'm going to become an introvert, bury myself in work and sort out allll the things before I face the world again". Turns out, things weren't going wrong, they were just happening, and that was that. No balls needed... no bad luck, just things. Sleeves needed rolling up, and life needed to play out, and I needed to do my best, and I did. I'm grateful I had so much work to help over the last year (thank you if you have commissioned me for any. The tech industry has been so incredibly supportive!) but wow have I felt cut off from the world. 
Maybe I needed to isolate myself a bit, but I'm kind of over it now. As with any moment of realisation though, I definitely learned some blindingly obvious lessons in doing so: excellent friends and people are excellent, they make life worth living. When you work to help something or someone you love, you run the risk of losing yourself a bit, or a lot, keep tabs on it, or surround yourself with genuine people who do it for you (and listen to them). Living to work can be easy to do if you love your work, or money, but a life worked and not lived is impossible to undo. Some people need to work 24/7 to survive, for us lucky ones who don't, let's not squander the luxury of choice. Finally, family is important, but so is your own health and happiness üßò‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è...
